<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1528,2020]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1528,1553]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Recognized by the amber-brown basic coloration, and polished pronotum and scutellum that are not pruinosed or shagreened, in addition to the characters mentioned in generic diagnosis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1528,2020]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,339,1600,1625]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[351,407,1601,1625]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Male</emphasis>
: Body generally amber-brown; dorsal surface shiny. Antenna yellowish brown, except for darkened segment IV. Pronotum and scutellum polished; anterior lobe of pronotum transversely wrinkled; apical scutellar spine dark brown; ostiolar peritreme creamy yellow. Hemelytron less shining, with three white maculae each on middle clavus, and base and subapical part of corium; corium chestnut brown posterior to apical white macula (anterior to cuneal fracture); cuneus fuscous; membrane smoky brown, except for pale, translucent apical and posterior margins. All coxae and legs pale brown. Male genital segment widely infuscate. 
<emphasis box="[1092,1257,1781,1805]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1277,1349,1780,1804]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,2007,2030]" captionTargetBox="[157,1412,534,1955]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,517,1986]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male genitalia of Artchawakomius species named on the figure." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/214854/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[1333,1349,1780,1804]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
): Right paramere somewhat tapered toward apex; apical membranous area of endosoma not developed. 
<emphasis box="[1188,1270,1817,1841]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Female</emphasis>
: Unknown.
</paragraph>
